        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(discord): log warnings instead of silently swallowing component interaction errors",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\n`extensions/discord/src/monitor/agent-components-reply.ts` and `extensions/discord/src/monitor/exec-approvals.ts` use empty `catch {}` blocks to silently swallow errors from Discord interaction replies. When these replies fail (expired interaction, network issue, permission error), there is zero diagnostic output — making debugging impossible.\n\n## Changes\n\n- `agent-components-reply.ts`: `catch {}` → `catch (err) { console.warn(\"discord component reply failed\", ...) }`\n- `exec-approvals.ts`: 4 sites → `catch (err) { console.warn(\"discord exec approval ... failed\", ...) }`\n- `test/_proof_discord_silent_catch.mts`: calls `replySilently` with throwing mock interaction, verifies console.warn (4 PASS, 0 FAIL)\n\nLabel: bugfix | merge-risk: 🟢 minimal | AI-assisted\n\n## Evidence\n\n### Real behavior proof — calls replySilently with throwing interaction (L2)\n\n```\n$ node --import tsx test/_proof_discord_silent_catch.mts\n\nPASS  console.warn called on reply failure :: calls=1\nPASS  warning contains diagnostic prefix :: msg=discord component reply failed Unknown interaction\nPASS  warning includes error message\nPASS  console.warn NOT called on successful reply :: calls=0\n\n[proof] 4 PASS, 0 FAIL\n```\n\nThe proof imports the ACTUAL `replySilently` function, calls it with a mock interaction that throws on `reply()`, and verifies that `console.warn` is called with the expected diagnostic message. It also verifies that successful replies do NOT produce warnings.",
